               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>This manuscript consists mostly of samples of Sāñcīpat, Agar wood bark prepared to be used as writing support. This practice is common in Assam. Most folios are blank, except for <locus facs="10">one</locus> which contains a few lines in <term xml:lang="sa">Śāradā</term> script from what seems to be the <title xml:lang="sa">Kulālikāmnāya</title>. The incipit closely parallels 4.111-112 of the critical text of Goudriaan &amp; Schoterman (1988, 191). The scribal hand as well as the marginal title seem to be identical to those of Sanscrit 1442.3.</p>
<p>A <locus facs="2">note</locus> in Palmyr Cordier's hand describes the process by which the folios are prepared, translated into French from an <ref target="https://archive.org/details/journalofasiatic6318asia/page/107/mode/1up">1894 article</ref> in the Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal by E. A. Gait.</p></summary>
                  
